The original Heisenberg model is defined by taking spin-1 particles on a 1d lattice, and defining a two-particle interaction between them using the generators of SU(2), leading to the following Hamiltonian:

In 1983, Haldane made a conjecture for SU(2)-symmetric chains, stating that half-integer spins lead to gapless chains, while integer spins lead to gapped systems. This has been numerically verified, and one of the most famous examples is the Haldane gap for spin 1 ( I Affleck 1989 J. Phys.: Condens. Matter 1 3047):

Afterwards, the conjecture has been generalised to SU(n) chains in the symmetric representations, for a rank-p representation, a gapless phase is predicted if p and n are coprime, otherwise a finite energy gap is present. The base of these conjectures is rooted in field theoretic arguments, where fractional topological excitations are able to generate a mass gap.

These theoretical arguments have been reproduced using numerics, first found by (Gozel, S., Nataf, P., Mila, F., 2020. Haldane Gap of the Three-Box Symmetric SU(3) Chain. Phys. Rev. Lett. 125, 057202). They indeed report a gap for the rank-3 SU(3) chain.

In tensor network language, the two-body interaction may be built in a manifest symmetric way by considering the diagram below, where the external indices are fixed to act according to the spin 1 representations, while the red line carries the adjoint representation, i.e. the representation under which the generators transform.

This interpretation supports a generalisation of Heisenberg interactions to any Lie group, in particular to SU(N). Furthermore, this symmetric representation is well defined, as the only remaining degrees of freedom are the external representations, fixed by the model, and a multiplicative constant which defines the energy scale.

Additionally, for software that supports non-Abelian symmetries with multiple fusion (for example TensorKit.jl with MPSKitl.jl in Julia, or our group's "MatlabTrack") it is possible to boost the performance of the algorithms tremendously, allowing for analysis up to bigger bond dimension.

Finally it is worth mentioning that for self-conjugate representations of SU(3) chains, a gap is also expected, and spontaneously broken parity symmetry is predicted for half of these cases.
